The Familiar at the New Antisemitism
Why do so many survivors of the Holocaust feel emerging threats to Judaism, even before they become generally visible?
Because they know that the supposedly "harmless" hints can turn into accusations and eventually lead to discrimination, which is then legally entrenched.
At this point, hysteria sets in.
The survivors sound the alarm, because they know what's at stake.
By doing so, they strengthen our democracies in a way that only they can.
We listen to the survivors so that we too may survive.
Since the first round of the French presidential elections, it is clear that we have every reason to listen.
But not only demagogues like Jean-Marie Le Pen or other coarse right-wing extremists in Europe cause problems.
In the 20th century, people who saw themselves as "intellectuals" often became bystanders to fascism or communism without joining a party with the corresponding ideological background.
In the 21st century, we are dealing with people - the "educated bourgeoisie" in connection with the mass media, politics, government, and universities - who condemn Israel in a language that often reminds us of that of bystanders to these antidemocratic movements.
This is not the majority opinion in the Western world - not yet, fortunately - but it is the voice of a powerful and influential minority.
At this point, the example of the French ambassador to the United Kingdom should be mentioned: recently, he referred to Israel as "this damned little country" at a dinner party in London.
His vulgar language is not particularly frightening.
What is more alarming, however, are the reactions to it.
Neither was he recalled by his government, nor did the Blair government demand his recall. In the public eye, the affair was dismissed as a scandal.
The French press presented the ambassador seriously as a victim of British gossip and not of his own despicable attitude.
Unfortunately, the French ambassador to the United Kingdom has several allies among Europe's elites.
However, Ambassador Bernard did us a service: Through him, it became clear how widespread these new anti-Jewish sentiments are.
As a columnist aptly put it: Israel has become an object of hate, whose name one dares not speak.
We but must not only dare to speak out, we are even obligated to do so.
In the face of daily attacks on Jews and synagogues in France, we must not remain silent.
It is a shame for all of Europe that so many French Jews cannot send their children to school without worrying about their safety.
Anti-Semitic incidents are reported elsewhere as well. In Berlin and London, in Switzerland, Italy, Sweden, the Netherlands, and in parts of Eastern Europe.
We must not remain silent about the normalization of Holocaust denial. Nor must we remain silent about the comparisons made by anti-Semites and anti-Zionists between Israel and the Third Reich.
While Israeli soldiers are portrayed as rapists and cold-blooded killers in a Palestinian TV show, a Syrian newspaper wrote that we "must confront the new Nazi plague that is emerging in Israel".
The Mufti of Jerusalem said: "It's not my fault that Hitler hated Jews. People hate them almost everywhere".
During a TV broadcast of a Friday prayer in Palestinian television, the preacher called on Muslims to "show no mercy to Jews. Wherever you are, kill them and these Americans, who are just like them".
When thinking about anti-Semitism, we should remember that it always starts with Jews, but never ends with Jews.
If Jew hatred is not checked, it almost always leads to attacks on other groups and minorities and ultimately undermines democratic institutions and the rule of law.
The fight against anti-Semitism is therefore the task of Jews as well as non-Jews.
The targets in this fight are currently less clear than ever before, because an astonishing aspect of today's anti-Semitism is its flexibility.
Although the goal of anti-Semitism remains the same - namely, to attack Jews - it still changes its face, strategy, rationalizations, and even vocabulary.
In the past, the Jewish religion was the target.
When this did not yield results, Jews were expelled or killed.
When racial theory swept people off their feet in the 19th century, Jews were attacked because of their membership in a supposedly evil race.
With the existence of the State of Israel as a source of pride and protection for most Jews, Zionism is now slandered as a racist ideology today.
I do not equate criticism of Israel with anti-Semitism.
Just as with other nations, it is indeed legitimate to be critical of certain political strategies and decisions made by Israel.
However, anti-Zionism is becoming increasingly similar to anti-Semitism.
Antizionists sometimes claim that they are not against the Jews, but "only" against the Jewish state.
Imagine someone saying: "I am only against the existence of the United Kingdom, but I am not anti-British!"
Or if someone claimed: "I love the Swedish people, but Sweden should be abolished."
You would not believe them.
It is difficult to love or respect a people, but hate their state.
Yet, there are people who claim to be able to do exactly that when it comes to Israel.
In various UN organizations, Israel-bashing is on the agenda.
This demonization of the only democratic state in the Middle East is a core point of this new anti-Semitism.
When Israel is described as "the enemy of all that is good and the source of all evil," then the "doctrine of contempt" is circulating within the UN, as expressed by Professor Irwin Cotler, a member of the Canadian Parliament.
This permanent portrayal of a nation as the enemy of humanity is, in truth, a campaign against the Jewish people.
So liegen den zahlreichen anti-Jewish attacks in many countries the demonizations of Israel at the root, which employ an anti-Semitic terminology.
Attacks on synagogues are often triggered by the use of this slanderous language in connection with the Middle East.
Compared to previous anti-Jewish outbursts, today's anti-Semitism involves less attacks on individual Jews and more an attack on the "collective Jew," namely the State of Israel.
Such attacks have, however, set off a chain reaction of attacks on individual Jews and Jewish institutions across all of Europe and Latin America.
In the past, the most dangerous anti-Semites were those who wanted to make the world Jew-free.
The most dangerous anti-Semites today are those who want to make the world Jew-state-free.
